[2] Arkansas
Date: Mon 19 Dec 2016 5:00PM CST
Source: Arkansas Matters [edited]
http://www.arkansasmatters.com/news/local-news/arkansas-worst-mumps-outbreak-since-1970s/623061868


The Arkansas mumps outbreak continues with about 2200 cases actively under investigation, a type of outbreak that hasn't been seen since the 1970s.

In a meeting at the Capitol [Mon 19 Dec 2016], lawmakers got an update on where the outbreak started and what may contribute to its spread, including vaccine exemptions. Health officials have tracked the strain to an initial outbreak at an Iowa college. They say 12 new cases were reported last week [week of 12 Dec 2016].

"Mumps has a long incubation period, around 12-25 days, so we could see an upsurge next week. We're just going to keep doing what we know to do, until it goes away," said Dr Nate Smith, Director and State Health Officer at the Arkansas Department of Health.

The Health Department says mumps has spread from Arkansas to Texas and Oklahoma. The Marshallese population in Northwest Arkansas has been especially hard-hit. About 60 percent of the region's cases have affected people in that community.

[Byline: Ellen Lampe]

